				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Casual player needing help<a name="67444"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 19 04 11:32 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Hello everyone,
<br />

<br />
I've lurked round EQDiva for a long time (I've had my bard since sometime in 2001) but I've never registered or posted before.  I'm only a casual player and have taken some fairly big hiatuses due to work, moving and other interests.  My bard is my main character and is currently level 54 with no AA points as yet.  I have all the expansions except Gates of Discord and Omens of War, and I play on Drinal.
<br />

<br />
I'm now running into some problems.  Whilst I'm able to successfully chant-kite mobs, it's slow and fairly boring going, and I'm also woefully poor.  I have only 7000 plat and I'm still entirely in Lambent armor except for the arms.  I'm trying to get CoV faction to do the Skyshrine armor quests but it's such slow going without Kael raids and even once I'm an ally I'll need a lot of help to do the armor quests themselves.  I can't afford singing steel and I don't think I can solo the mobs that drop it, so I'm pretty well stuck.  I've done all the easier bits of the epic but again, I'm now to a point where I need things like Phinny's spine which I obviously can't get alone.
<br />

<br />
My guild is nice but they don't raid much, and if they do I don't think it's on a regular schedule so I tend not to know in advance if it's happening.  Because I don't always have access to the computer (I have to share with my husband) this makes it hard for me to &quot;book time&quot; to play - I just have to squeeze in time as and when.
<br />

<br />
So basically, I need advice.  I've found several high-level guilds that raid regularly but they're either not accepting new members or only accepting people much more advanced and dedicated than I am.  Do these raids tend to allow the odd non-guildmember to join?  I'm not great I guess but I think I'm pretty reasonable; I can follow directions, I try not to get in the way and I help out wherever I can.  Am I just stuck for advancement/gear upgrades/experience unless I'm willing to spend a lot more time playing than I currently do?  And with EQII due out next month, is it worth it?
<br />

<br />
I'm just not sure, I feel kind of lost.  I hate to give up on a character I do really quite like and in whom I have invested a lot of time (if somewhat sporadically) but I'm not sure quite where to go with her.
<br />

<br />
Sorry to be so long-winded! <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-10.gif" border="0" alt="Blushing" hspace="2" /></span></td>
